joined by "NewsHour" regular
Marcia Coyle

10:05.939 --> 10:07.474 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of "The National Law Journal."

10:07.507 --> 10:08.641 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Hi there, Marcia.

10:08.675 --> 10:10.410 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE, "The National Law
Journal":
Hi, Audie.

10:10.443 --> 10:12.111 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
AUDIE CORNISH: So, what
precisely are the
judges hearing the arguments
about tonight?

10:12.145 --> 10:13.913 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What is at stake?

10:13.947 --> 10:17.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: The government is
going to be
arguing, first of all, that
Minnesota and

10:17.517 --> 10:21.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the state of Washington do not
have the right
to challenge the president's
executive order

10:22.021 --> 10:23.723 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on immigration.

10:23.756 --> 10:28.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The president, they will argue,
has power
under federal law and the
Constitution to

10:28.161 --> 10:34.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
issue this order, and this order
itself doesn't
violate the Constitution, either
because of

10:34.234 --> 10:38.404 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
religious discrimination or any
other provision
of the Constitution.

10:38.438 --> 10:43.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The states are going to come
back, and they're
going to say the lower court's
order is not

10:43.309 --> 10:48.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
appealable by the government, we
have a right
to be in court to challenge it,
this order

10:48.848 --> 10:55.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
exceeds the president's power
and violates
federal law and the
Constitution, and it does

10:55.688 --> 10:57.624 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
violate religious rights under
the Constitution.

10:57.657 --> 11:02.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AUDIE CORNISH: Now, the states
have said that
they know the president has
broad authority

11:02.262 --> 11:06.132 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to be in control of who comes in
and out of
the country.

11:06.165 --> 11:09.302 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So what do we know about how the
Supreme Court
feels about this?

11:09.335 --> 11:13.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What's the case law out there
that tells us
whether or not the president
does have some

11:13.072 --> 11:14.774 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
limits on his power there?

11:14.807 --> 11:18.845 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: Well, the Supreme
Court has
held in a number of cases over
many years

11:18.878 --> 11:25.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the president has broad
power under the
Immigration and Nationality Act
and also under

11:25.485 --> 11:29.322 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
his inherent power to conduct
foreign affairs.

11:29.355 --> 11:32.458 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In the area of immigration, he
has these broad
powers.

11:32.492 --> 11:39.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
However, at the same time, the
court has recognized,
because also over the years, we
have developed

11:39.499 --> 11:44.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a jurisprudence in this country
that recognizes
certain rights under the
Constitution, and

11:44.904 --> 11:50.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it is the interplay of how those
rights may
intersect with the president's
power that

11:50.376 --> 11:58.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
comes to play in this particular
case, rights
such as to be free of
nationality discrimination,

11:58.151 --> 12:03.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
religious discrimination, and to
have the
equal protection and due process
of law.

12:03.056 --> 12:07.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AUDIE CORNISH: People have been
talking about
these legal challenges as though
it's inevitable

12:07.360 --> 12:09.295 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that they will end up before the
Supreme Court.

12:09.329 --> 12:10.997 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Is that the case?

12:11.030 --> 12:14.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: We will have to
wait and see
what this three-judge panel does
with the

12:14.334 --> 12:16.369 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
appeal by the government.

12:16.402 --> 12:20.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ultimately, it may well get to
the Supreme
Court, but whether it will get
to the court

12:20.773 --> 12:23.710 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
quickly, I really don't know.

12:23.743 --> 12:30.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The court may decide that this
has been such
an early action, there's been no
full hearing

12:30.183 --> 12:35.088 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and full argument on the merits
of the challenge
to the president's order.

12:35.121 --> 12:39.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The court may want that to play
out a bit
in the lower court, as well as
in the other

12:39.993 --> 12:44.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
courts that are facing these
challenges right
now.

12:44.063 --> 12:49.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the other hand, it may be
convinced that
national security is of such a
great concern

12:49.202 --> 12:51.337 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that it ought to jump in.

12:51.371 --> 12:56.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And also, just remember, this is
still an
eight-justice court, and last
term, when it

12:56.909 --> 13:04.283 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
was faced with a major
immigration case involving
states' authority to sue to
challenge an executive

13:04.317 --> 13:10.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
action, as well as the scope of
a president's
power in the area of
immigration, it split

13:10.657 --> 13:18.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
4-4, and was unable to resolve
some of those
issues and give guidance to what
would -- I'm

13:18.431 --> 13:22.835 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sure the Ninth Circuit would
like the see
tonight in those particular
areas.

13:22.869 --> 13:29.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the court may want to wait
until it has
a ninth justice and doesn't face
the possibility

13:29.509 --> 13:30.910 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of a deadlock.

13:30.943 --> 13:34.914 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AUDIE CORNISH: In the meantime,
these arguments
are being held tonight.

13:34.947 --> 13:38.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just remind us why this case is
different
from all the other legal
challenges that have

13:38.718 --> 13:40.520 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
propped up that have had
specific plaintiffs.

13:40.553 --> 13:42.288 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA COYLE: Right.

13:42.321 --> 13:47.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, this case in particular,
because the
lower court judge, Judge Robart,
he issued

13:47.660 --> 13:54.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a nationwide injunction against
the president's
order, and so that affects
everybody.

13:54.834 --> 13:56.302 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It affects all of the states.

13:56.335 --> 14:00.506 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It affects the people who are
trying to come
into the country as well.

14:00.540 --> 14:04.877 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the other courts have issued
more limited
orders.

14:04.911 --> 14:08.181 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think that the attention
now is here.

14:08.214 --> 14:13.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The government wants this one
resolved because
of the sweeping impact it has
under a nationwide

14:13.786 --> 14:15.555 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
injunction.

14:15.588 --> 14:18.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AUDIE CORNISH: And can you give
us a little
preview, if it goes one way or
another, are

14:18.391 --> 14:20.660 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there limits about who can
appeal, who cannot
appeal?

14:20.693 --> 14:25.865 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: Well, right now,
before the
three-judge panel, it's what we
called a temporary

14:25.898 --> 14:26.999 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
restraining order.

14:27.033 --> 14:29.769 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, generally, those aren't
appealable.

14:29.802 --> 14:35.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the panel can look at it as
being akin
to another type of order that is
appealable.

14:35.641 --> 14:42.749 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, depending on whether this
panel wants
to reach the merits, it may.

14:42.782 --> 14:44.617 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It may not.

14:44.650 --> 14:49.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It may send the case back to
Judge Robart
to have that full hearing that
generally follows

14:49.555 --> 14:51.357 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a temporary restraining order.

14:51.390 --> 14:54.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AUDIE CORNISH: And we will be
hearing more
tonight on what happens with
that case.

14:54.360 --> 14:55.762 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: Yes, we will.

14:55.795 --> 14:57.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AUDIE CORNISH: Marcia Coyle,
thank you so
much for speaking with us.

14:57.997 --> 15:05.738 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: My pleasure.

15:05.772 --> 15:13.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: One charge the
president and
his team have raised repeatedly
in recent

15:13.279 --> 15:19.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
days is his claim that the news
media either
ignore or undercovers terrorist
incidents.

15:19.585 --> 15:24.724 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On Monday, the president himself
said -- quote
-- "The dishonest press doesn't
want to report

15:24.757 --> 15:26.526 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on terrorist attacks."

15:26.559 --> 15:30.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That was followed by the White
House issuing
a list of attacks that it
contends didn't

15:30.696 --> 15:32.431 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
get enough press attention.

15:32.465 --> 15:37.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Philip Bump, who reports for The
Washington
Post, has been looking into the
accuracy of

15:37.170 --> 15:38.137 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the president's claims.

15:38.171 --> 15:40.239 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And he joins me now from New
York.

15:40.273 --> 15:45.211 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, Philip, just to be clear,
what exactly
did the president himself say?

15:45.244 --> 15:47.880 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And distinguish that from what
his press secretary
said.

15:47.914 --> 15:50.583 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
®MD-BO /PHILIP BUMP, The
Washington Post:
And it's an absolutely critical
distinction.

15:50.616 --> 15:54.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the president, speaking to
the United
States Central Command, said
that the media

15:54.220 --> 15:58.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wasn't reporting, that, for
whatever reason,
implying that there was some
bias involved,

15:58.424 --> 16:00.626 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the media wasn't reporting about
terror attacks.

16:00.660 --> 16:04.096 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The White House's press
secretary then came
back and modified that, tried to
soften it

16:04.130 --> 16:07.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and say, well, what he meant to
say is, these
things have been underreported.

16:07.567 --> 16:11.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That was the point at which they
issued this
list of 78 attacks that occurred
between 2014

16:11.804 --> 16:13.539 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and 2016.

16:13.573 --> 16:18.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, you went over
this list
of 78 different attacks that
they put down

16:18.244 --> 16:19.378 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and handed out.

16:19.412 --> 16:20.780 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And what did you find?

16:20.813 --> 16:24.083 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PHILIP BUMP: I didn't find any
that hadn't
actually been reported.

16:24.116 --> 16:25.685 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's the bar that the
president set.

16:25.718 --> 16:26.853 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's important to remember.

16:26.886 --> 16:28.487 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He said they had not been
reported.

16:28.521 --> 16:31.657 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Each of these 78, I had found
had been reported.

16:31.691 --> 16:33.593 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ThinkProgress, a liberal site,
went back.

16:33.626 --> 16:37.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They found 17,000 news articles
in the first
week after each of these attacks
covering

16:37.830 --> 16:40.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all these attacks, 17,000
articles covering
these 78 attacks.

16:40.566 --> 16:43.736 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So it's certainly the case that
these things
had been reported.

16:43.769 --> 16:47.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Underreported, of course, is
very subjective,
and that's really where the
administration

16:47.573 --> 16:50.409 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
right now is putting its
emphasis on making
that point.

16:50.443 --> 16:54.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, just to
back up a little
bit, there were a number of
terrorist attacks

16:54.347 --> 16:56.215 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in here that were clearly
covered.

16:56.249 --> 17:01.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, some would argue they
were overcovered,
from Orlando to San Bernardino
to the Paris

17:02.021 --> 17:03.556 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
attacks, Brussels, and so on.

17:03.589 --> 17:05.358 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PHILIP BUMP: That's exactly
right.

17:05.391 --> 17:09.528 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that that's why it's
very safe
to assume that the motivation
for releasing

17:09.562 --> 17:12.932 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this list wasn't necessarily to
make this
point about being underreported.

17:12.965 --> 17:17.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yes, to include on this list
something like
the San Bernardino attack or the
Orlando attack,

17:17.603 --> 17:22.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which got saturation coverage
for days on
end, justifiably, to include
those on a list

17:22.441 --> 17:26.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of things being underreported
seems to suggest
the point of the list was in
fact the list

17:26.545 --> 17:30.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
itself, in that there were all
these terror
attacks that the administration
at this moment,

17:30.316 --> 17:34.420 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with this court battle, going
wants to make
people aware that terrorism
still exists as

17:34.453 --> 17:36.255 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a big problem.

17:36.289 --> 17:39.558 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But, Philip Bump,
you also
did find some that didn't get
that much coverage.

17:39.592 --> 17:42.962 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Most of them occurred overseas,
is that right,
outside the United States?

17:42.995 --> 17:45.164 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PHILIP BUMP: That's exactly
right.

17:45.197 --> 17:50.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yes, so the scale of the attacks
here range
from the attack in Paris, which
was a multipronged

17:50.236 --> 17:55.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
attack, at a soccer stadium and
a music hall
and cafes, to stabbing attacks
on people -- military

17:55.841 --> 17:57.443 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
officials in Egypt, for example.

17:57.476 --> 18:00.279 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There was a huge range of what
is included
in this.

18:00.313 --> 18:04.083 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A lot of the attacks, no one was
killed, not
necessarily that that should be
the standard

18:04.116 --> 18:06.385 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by which we say a terrorist
attack is good
or bad.

18:06.419 --> 18:10.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the fact that all of these
things were
packaged together as one whole,
suggesting

18:10.656 --> 18:14.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this is, therefore, a threat to
the United
States, which was the clear
implication, I

18:14.160 --> 18:15.895 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
think is worth noting.

18:15.928 --> 18:19.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, the bottom
line is that
what the president stated is not
accurate,

18:19.632 --> 18:23.669 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that the press has ignored most
terrorist
attacks.

18:23.703 --> 18:31.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, to go beyond that, you
point out in the
article this concept of working
the refs.

18:31.243 --> 18:36.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The White House approach to
talking to the
press about what it's going to
do or not going

18:36.716 --> 18:41.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to do in covering something
that's coming
up, explore that with us for a
second.

18:41.053 --> 18:42.755 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PHILIP BUMP: Sure.

18:42.788 --> 18:46.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So there's this idea of working
with the refs,
essentially looking as the media
as being

18:46.759 --> 18:48.094 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
referees.

18:48.127 --> 18:50.029 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's this concept that
carries over from
sports, obviously.

18:50.062 --> 18:54.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the idea is to try and shape
the behavior
of the media by criticizing the
media in a

18:54.800 --> 18:56.168 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
very deliberate way.

18:56.202 --> 18:58.971 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so what Donald Trump said, I
don't think
that this was planned.

18:59.005 --> 19:02.375 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think he was irritated in the
moment at
the media, made these comments.

19:02.408 --> 19:04.477 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I can't obviously say that with
certainty.

19:04.510 --> 19:07.146 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think what Sean Spicer,
the press secretary
did, was very strategic.

19:07.179 --> 19:11.517 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And he said, this is an
opportunity for us
to try and get this list of 78
attacks out

19:11.550 --> 19:18.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in from of the media, and at the
