at this prison.

22:16.001 --> 22:18.070 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Can you tell me, who were these
people?

22:18.103 --> 22:22.107 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SUNJEEV BERY: There were
thousands of civilians,
as well as some ex-military
officers, who

22:22.141 --> 22:25.544 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are held at Saydnaya prison in
Saydnaya, Syria.

22:25.578 --> 22:29.248 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We estimate that between 10,000
and 20,000
people are held there now.

22:29.281 --> 22:34.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for years, on a weekly
basis, as many
as 50 people have been hanged in
mass executions

22:34.386 --> 22:36.188 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
by the Syrian government at this
prison.

22:36.222 --> 22:40.059 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And are these
people who
are picked up -- what are the
crimes that

22:40.092 --> 22:41.760 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
they're accused of?

22:41.794 --> 22:44.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SUNJEEV BERY: Many of them are
perceived to
be opposition to the government,
although

22:44.363 --> 22:49.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when you're doing this kind of
mass arrest,
mass torture and miss execution,
who knows

22:49.902 --> 22:51.837 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what the individual people's
backgrounds are?

22:51.870 --> 22:56.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, of course, peaceful,
nonviolent opposition
to a government is certainly not
a crime.

22:56.775 --> 23:01.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But with that background, many
of them are
subjected to forced confessions
through extraordinarily

23:01.814 --> 23:08.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
brutal torture, and once that
confession is
put via ink to paper, then the
execution process

23:08.220 --> 23:09.989 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
begins.

23:10.022 --> 23:13.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I understand a
lot of the
documentation for this report
came from people

23:13.158 --> 23:15.194 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
who witnessed what's going on in
there.

23:15.227 --> 23:19.732 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I understand that there is some
kind of a
trial process, so-called trial.

23:19.765 --> 23:21.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Can you explain a little bit
about what goes
on?

23:21.634 --> 23:23.402 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SUNJEEV BERY: Sure.

23:23.435 --> 23:26.272 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And just to put it in
perspective, the so-called
trial is a total of one to three
minutes.

23:26.305 --> 23:27.840 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: One to three
minutes' long?

23:27.873 --> 23:30.776 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SUNJEEV BERY: One to three
minutes per person,
who is then later executed.

23:30.809 --> 23:35.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So you have thousands of people
in these prisons
subjected to extraordinary
brutal torture

23:35.281 --> 23:39.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in complete silence, living
under rules of
complete silence, routine
deaths.

23:39.985 --> 23:45.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A certain percentage of the
population in
this prison are then taken to
trials via a

23:45.557 --> 23:52.298 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
military field court, a
so-called court, in
a suburb of Damascus, where,
during a one-to-three-minute

23:52.331 --> 23:59.538 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
trial, with, of course, no
lawyer present,
no due process at all, in 60 to
180 seconds,

23:59.571 --> 24:01.373 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they are sentenced to death.

24:01.407 --> 24:04.877 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That death sentence is then
rubber-stamped
by higher authorities up to the
highest levels

24:04.910 --> 24:08.447 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of government, and then later
they are tortured
and hung to death.

24:08.480 --> 24:12.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The thing that
was so striking
to me, among many, in this
report was the

24:12.351 --> 24:18.724 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
bureaucracy, the documentation
of it, the
fingerprinting, the getting
witnesses to sign

24:18.757 --> 24:23.896 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
that they had never been
mistreated, getting
doctors to certify that all
these deaths occurred

24:23.929 --> 24:25.764 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
because of natural causes.

24:25.798 --> 24:29.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Why do you think that the regime
goes to these
lengths to basically catalogue
their own war

24:29.635 --> 24:31.270 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
crimes?

24:31.303 --> 24:34.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SUNJEEV BERY: It is difficult to
know why
the regime is so
bureaucratically efficient

24:34.907 --> 24:38.344 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in its documentation of its
crimes against
humanity.

24:38.377 --> 24:42.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One possibility may be that the
senior levels
of the government, perhaps even
including

24:42.481 --> 24:47.486 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Bashar al-Assad, want
to know that
the crimes against humanity that
they are

24:47.519 --> 24:52.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
likely to be ordering are, in
fact, being
carried out by the military and
the intelligence

24:53.025 --> 24:54.727 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
bureaucracy.

24:54.760 --> 24:58.464 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so with each of these
executions, the
executions are signed, either by
the grand

24:58.497 --> 25:04.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
