and secretaries
were accused of overreach.

32:29.614 --> 32:30.682 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

32:30.715 --> 32:33.718 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They faced massive backlash over
federal initiatives.

32:33.752 --> 32:37.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What has that shown us about the
limits of
power for the education
secretary?

32:37.289 --> 32:42.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EMMA BROWN: Yes, the Obama
administration
took the power of the Education
Department

32:42.327 --> 32:43.361 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to its limits.

32:43.395 --> 32:45.597 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And what we saw was a backlash
from Congress.

32:45.630 --> 32:51.770 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Congress didn't appreciate that,
and, in the
end, you know, passed with
overwhelming majorities

32:51.803 --> 32:58.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a new federal education law, the
Every Student
Succeeds Act, that really reined
in the education

32:58.543 --> 33:03.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
